Problem 1

aapl_df = read.csv("../AAPL_March16_2020_March16_2022.csv", header=TRUE)
amzn_df = read.csv("../AMZN_March16_2020_March16_2022.csv", header=TRUE)
googl_df = read.csv("../GOOGL_March16_2020_March16_2022.csv", header=TRUE)
nasdaq_df = read.csv("../Nasdaq_March16_2000_March 16_2022.csv", header=TRUE)
mu_f = 0.025 / 253
dates = nrow(aapl_df)

aapl_ret = aapl_df$Adj.Close[2:dates] / aapl_df$Adj.Close[1:dates-1] - 1
amzn_ret = amzn_df$Adj.Close[2:dates] / amzn_df$Adj.Close[1:dates-1] - 1
googl_ret = googl_df$Adj.Close[2:dates] / googl_df$Adj.Close[1:dates-1] - 1
nasdaq_ret = nasdaq_df$Adj.Close[2:dates] / nasdaq_df$Adj.Close[1:dates-1] - 1

aapl_exc = aapl_ret - mu_f
amzn_exc = amzn_ret - mu_f
googl_exc = googl_ret - mu_f
nasdaq_exc = nasdaq_ret - mu_f
lm(aapl_exc ~ nasdaq_exc)
lm(amzn_exc ~ nasdaq_exc)
lm(googl_exc ~ nasdaq_exc)
aapl_por = 1.085 ^ 2 * var(nasdaq_ret) / var(aapl_ret)
amzn_por = 0.962 ^ 2 * var(nasdaq_ret) / var(amzn_ret)
googl_por = 0.962 ^ 2 * var(nasdaq_ret) / var(googl_ret)

We have the following result

\(\alpha\) \(\beta\) Portion of Market Variance
Apple 6.3E-4 1.085 0.669
Amazon 1.33E-6 0.962 0.513
Google 5.99E-4 0.962 0.637
  1. For the empirical variance, we have
ret_df <- data.frame(aapl_ret, amzn_ret, googl_ret)

For the covariance from regression, we have

Apple Amazon Google
Apple 2.87E-4 2.547E-4 2.547E-4

There is obvious difference between the empirical covariance and regression-derived covariance, I think its due to the fact that our assumption is not valid. The value of \(\alpha\) is not negligible and the errors may be dependent.

Problem 2

ts_aapl <- ts(aapl_df$Adj.Close)
ts_amzn <- ts(amzn_df$Adj.Close)
ts_googl <- ts(googl_df$Adj.Close)
ts_nasdaq <- ts(nasdaq_df$Adj.Close)
ts_aapl_ret <- ts(aapl_ret)
ts_amzn_ret <- ts(amzn_ret)
ts_googl_ret <- ts(googl_ret)
ts_nasdaq_ret <- ts(nasdaq_ret)
par(mfrow=c(5,1))
plot(ts_aapl, col="red")
plot(ts_amzn, col="orange")
plot(ts_googl, col="blue")
plot(ts_nasdaq, col="green")
plot(ts_aapl_ret, col="red")
lines(ts_amzn_ret, col="orange")
lines(ts_googl_ret, col="blue")
lines(ts_nasdaq_ret, col="green")

For Apple and Google, the plots shows a similar rising for both of them. It makes sense since they have similar portion of market variance. While for Amazon, there are more drawbacks and the rising trend is not so obvious after the 100th timestamp. Its also reflected in the lower portion of market variance. Now, all stocks are starting to decrease, as shown in the Nasdaq Index, since they all have a \(\beta\) close to 1.

par(mfrow=c(4,1))
acf(ts_aapl, col="red")
acf(ts_amzn, col="orange")
acf(ts_googl, col="blue")
acf(ts_nasdaq, col="green")

The plots show that there is an extremely high ACF even after a lag of 25. It makes perfect sense since its unlikely for the price to change too much in a short interval. Therefore, the close price is not stationary since the mean is not zero and there is a trend.

par(mfrow=c(4,1))
acf(ts_aapl_ret, col="red")
acf(ts_amzn_ret, col="orange")
acf(ts_googl_ret, col="blue")
acf(ts_nasdaq_ret, col="green")

Most of ACF lie in the confidence interval, since return doesnt have too much relation to each other in time. Therefore, Id conclude that the return is stationary.

Problem 3

  1. \[ \mu_X=\mu_Z-\mu_Y\\ \gamma_X(h)=\text{Cov}(Y_{t+h}-Z_{t+h}, Y_t-Z_t)=\gamma_Y(h)+\gamma_Z(h)=\frac{\sigma_Y^2\alpha_Y^{|h|}}{1-\alpha_Y^2}+\frac{\sigma_Z^2\alpha_Z^{|h|}}{1-\alpha_Z^2}\\ \rho_X(h)=\frac{\gamma_X(h)}{\gamma_X(0)}=\frac{(1-\alpha_Z^2)\alpha_Y^{|h|}\sigma_Y^2+(1-\alpha_Y^2)\alpha_Z^{|h|}\sigma_Z^2}{(1-\alpha_Z^2)\sigma_Y^2+(1-\alpha_Y^2)\sigma_Z^2} \]

  2. \[ \mu_X=\mu_Y+\mu_Y\mu_Z\\ \gamma_X(h)=\text{Cov}(Y_{n+h}+Y_{n+h}Z_{n+h}, Y_n+Y_nZ_n)=\gamma_Y(h)+\gamma_{YZ}(h)+\text{Cov}(Y_{n+h}, Y_nZ_n)+\text{Cov}(Y_n, Y_{n+h}Z_{n+h})\\ \text{Cov}(Y_{n+h}, Y_nZ_n)=E[(Y_{n+h}-\mu_Y)(Y_nZ_n-\mu_Y\mu_Z)]=\mu_Z\gamma_Y(h)=\text{Cov}(Y_n, Y_{n+h}Z_{n+h})\\ \gamma_{YZ}(h)=\text{Cov}(Y_{n+h}Z_{n+h}, Y_nZ_n)=\text{Cov}(\alpha_Y\alpha_ZY_{n+h-1}Z_{n+h-1}+\alpha_ZZ_{n+h-1}\epsilon_Y+\alpha_YY_{n+h-1}\epsilon_Z+\epsilon_Y\epsilon_X, Y_nZ_n)\\ \gamma_{YZ}(h)=(\alpha_Y\alpha_Z)^{|h|}\text{Var}(Y_nZ_n)=(\alpha_Y\alpha_Z)^{|h|}(E[(Y_nZ_n)^2]-E[(Y_nZ_n)]^2)=(\alpha_Y\alpha_Z)^{|h|}(E[Y_n^2]E[Z_n^2]-\mu_Y^2\mu_Z^2)\\ E[Y_n^2]E[Z_n^2]=(\gamma_Y(0)+\mu_Y^2)(\gamma_Z(0)+\mu_Z^2)\\ \gamma_{YZ}(h)=(\alpha_Y\alpha_Z)^{|h|}(\frac{\sigma_Y^2\sigma_Z^2}{(1-\alpha_Y^2)(1-\alpha_Z^2)}+\frac{\sigma_Y^2\mu_Z^2}{1-\alpha_Y^2}+\frac{\sigma_Z^2\mu_Y^2}{1-\alpha_Z^2})\\ \gamma_X(h)=(1+2\mu_Z)\frac{\sigma_Y^2\alpha_Y^{|h|}}{1-\alpha_Y^2}+(\alpha_Y\alpha_Z)^{|h|}(\frac{\sigma_Y^2\sigma_Z^2}{(1-\alpha_Y^2)(1-\alpha_Z^2)}+\frac{\sigma_Y^2\mu_Z^2}{1-\alpha_Y^2}+\frac{\sigma_Z^2\mu_Y^2}{1-\alpha_Z^2}) \]

\[ \mu_X=2\mu_Y\\ \gamma_X(h)=\text{Cov}(Y_{n+h}+Y_{n+1+h},Y_n+Y_{n+1})=2\gamma_Y(0)+\gamma_Y(h+1)+\gamma_Y(|h-1|)=\frac{\sigma_Y^2}{1-\alpha_Y^2}(2+\alpha_Y^{|h+1|}+\alpha_Y^{|h-1|})\\ \]
